🔥 First Important Rule

A block is NOT an object by default in Ruby.

It is just a piece of code attached to a method call.

Example:

user.login { puts "Hello" }

That { puts "Hello" } is a block — but it’s not yet a Proc object.

🧠 What &block Actually Does

When you define:

def method_name(&block)
end

The & does ONE special thing:

It converts the block into a Proc object.

So:

Without & → block is just executable code

With &block → block becomes a Proc object you can store, pass, or call

✅ Example 1 — Without &
def test
  yield
end

test { puts "Hello" }

Here we use yield.

We can execute the block

But we cannot store it

We cannot pass it somewhere else

✅ Example 2 — With &block
def test(&block)
  block.call
end

test { puts "Hello" }

Now:

block is a Proc object

You can store it

You can pass it to another method

You can call it multiple times

🎯 Why Is & Needed?

Because Ruby must know:

"Ohhh, you want to convert this block into a real object."

The & is the conversion operator.

🔁 Very Important: & Works Both Ways
1️⃣ Block → Proc (in method definition)
def test(&block)
end

Converts block to Proc.

2️⃣ Proc → Block (in method call)
my_proc = Proc.new { puts "Hello" }

test(&my_proc)

Here & converts Proc back into a block.

🧠 Why Does Ruby Need This Conversion?

Because blocks are lightweight and fast.

Ruby keeps them special internally.

Only when you use &, Ruby wraps them inside a Proc object.

This improves performance.

🔥 Real Interview-Level Example
def wrapper(&block)
  puts "Before"
  block.call
  puts "After"
end

wrapper { puts "Inside" }

Output:

Before
Inside
After

Now imagine method_missing:

def method_missing(method_name, *args, &block)
  puts "Missing method"
end

If someone calls:

user.test { puts "Hello" }

Ruby passes that block into method_missing.

If you don’t accept &block,
Ruby will complain if a block was given.

🚀 When Do We Actually Need &block?

You only need it if:

You want to store the block

You want to pass it to another method

You want to call it manually with block.call

If you just want to execute once,
yield is simpler and faster.

⚡ Difference Between yield and &block

| yield                         | &block              |
| ----------------------------- | ------------------- |
| Faster                        | Slightly slower     |
| No object created             | Proc object created |
| Cannot pass to another method | Can be passed       |

🎯 Super Simple Summary

& means: “Convert block to Proc”

Without &, block is just attached code

With &, block becomes an object

